Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[West Nile virus transmission is active again this year (2020) in Florida. The location of human cases varies from location to location and number of human cases changes from year to year. For example, ArboNet maps (https://wwwn.cdc.gov/arbonet/Maps/ADB_Diseases_Map/index.html) show no cases so far this year (2020) in Florida; last year (2019), was relatively quiet with one case each in in Sumter and Duval counties, whereas 2018 was much more active with 46 cases scattered across the state. The current year's cases mentioned above are the 1st shown in Miami-Dade county since one case was shown in 2011. Apparently, the cases above have not yet been entered into ArboNet Maps.

WNV is maintained in a transmission cycle involving wild birds and _Culex_ mosquitoes, with spillover to humans and equine animals. Perhaps the wet conditions mentioned in the report above have provided abundant breeding sites for vector mosquitoes. Ongoing transmission of the virus will depend on abundance of vector mosquitoes juxtaposed with ample susceptible bird hosts. Nevertheless, avoidance of mosquito bites and vaccination of horses are prudent preventive measures to be adopted currently. Since WNV can infect equine animals and cause disease and death in them, vaccination should be carried our as soon as possible now that it is clear that WNV transmission is occurring. - Mod.TY

